@felixguendling situation B cannot be done from client perspective using the shape_dist_traveled, unless the client would scale the as the crow flies distance, or ignore the shape_dist_traveled altogether, or do some kind of map matching. I find it technically very interesting and well thought that GTFS has the option to express a longer distance than as-the-crow-flies between two shape points, since it allows for generatisation.

The "problem" within GTFS is that this calculation _might_ be different for all trips. There is no normalisation for shape_dist_traveled.

I am all for making this a requirement in the spec, but the 2 meter would be a best practice.

+1 Trillium

@skinkie The spec's Best Practices already make value statements regarding open data, so precedence has already been established. This change just adds stipulations to the already-existing best practice for publishing GTFS openly.

If your data is to be considered "public" and "directly...[and] openly downloadable" (https://gtfs.org/documentation/schedule/schedule-best-practices/), thus in compliance with Best Practices, it necessarily cannot simultaneously restrict access—based on geography or otherwise.

> I suggest to broaden "marathon" to sports events, or add "or other sports events". Such events may result in positive effects like additional services,

@hbruch great feedback, thanks! I changed the guidance in the proposed change from “marathon” to “sporting event.”

I appreciate your validation based on analyzing the text strings. That’s exactly how I figured we’d have to empirically validate that 90% goal, and I’m glad you already did it!
